<div type="translation" resp="part:argr part:vito">
<p>Gift of the noble Dhammā, pupil of the noble Retī.</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<p>For the contents, compare <ref target="DHARMA_INSEIAD00131.xml">EIAD 131</ref> and <ref target="DHARMA_INSEIAD00334.xml">EIAD 334</ref>. The inscription <ref target="DHARMA_INSEIAD00256.xml">EIAD 256</ref> was added at a later time above the present one.</p>     
</div>
<div type="bibliography">
<p>First edited and translated by Eugen Hultzsch whose own publication (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Hultzsch1883_01"/></bibl>) appeared a bit later than the first work dedicated to Amaravati by James Burgess  (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Burgess1882_01"/></bibl>), who made use of readings and translations furnished by Hultzsch. This digital edition by Arlo Griffiths &amp; Vincent Tournier from published estampages, from photographs and after autopsy of the stone.</p>
